adv_school_free: Emails, department advisor:  / - take phone calls, love letters, and promises of ranking you highly by a program with a grain of salt / - it's ok to send 5 top programs with love letters, but probably not worth your time emailing every single program as it will likely not make a big difference, don't lie about ranking #1 / - since the ranking system ranks off of your list you should go with your gut feeling and not whether or not you think you have a chance / - make sure to rank all prelims in each supplemental list for advanced programs, unless you would rather not match at all than go there (same w/adv or categorical) / - elective time may be very different for different programs, more doesn't mean better (elective time at some programs may have to be used to fulfill ACGME requirements) / - most IM prelims should satisfy ACGME requirements, some transitional years may not, double check to be safe / - be careful with 'pointed' questions (ex. asking lots of questions about pain fellowships) so late in the game, as programs generally like candidates who are open-minded / - programs can change their rank lists at any time before Feb 22, even if their ranking committees have already met / - going to residency in a different city can allow you to learn from other perspectives/medical systems / - if you enjoy being very involved and would like to help shape curriculum being a part of a new/young program may be good for you, however, you will be a guinea pig / - make sure to look at program specific out/inpatient models and diversity / - lots of home call may not be as good as it sounds, comes with its own set of challenges, depends on your personal preferences / - when looking at the reputation of a program, make sure that it is not just the hospital system that is well-known/run, but also the PM&R program itself / - free standing rehab centers provide good block-based immersion training but also come with its own challenges (having to manage codes, less support from other fields)
